        'Afferents that initiate swallowing: Sensory (afferent) input is provided by several cranial nerves. The trigeminal nerve (CN V) detects tactile sensations from the oral cavity and teeth. The facial nerve (CN VII) carries taste information from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. The glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) carries both touch and taste information from the posterior tongue and pharynx. The vagus nerve (CN X) carries sensory signals from the lower pharynx and larynx, particularly important for airway protection. Among these, CN IX and X play the most critical role in triggering the involuntary swallowing reflex. Mechanoreceptors in the oral mucosa, tongue, and palatoglossal arches detect the bolus.',
        'Major nuclei in the brainstem that integrate afferent inputs: These afferent signals are processed in the brainstem swallowing center, which consists primarily of two nuclei in the medulla oblongata. The nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS) serves as the primary sensory relay center - it receives incoming sensory input and communicates with the nucleus ambiguus (NA), which generates the motor response to coordinate muscle activity. Other motor nuclei involved: trigeminal motor nucleus (jaw movement), facial motor nucleus (lip and cheek control), hypoglossal nucleus (tongue movement). Swallowing centers: medulla and pons.',
