        'Sequence of events during swallowing: Tongue pushes back the bolus into the pharynx (initiation). All passages that are otherwise open must be closed (airways): soft palate closes nasal cavity, larynx is elevated, glottis closes, breathing stops (deglutition apnea). Vocal cords adduct, closing off the airway. Epiglottis folds down to cover the glottis. UES relaxes, allowing the bolus to pass into the esophagus. Peristaltic contractions then carry the bolus toward the stomach; LES relaxes to permit entry.'
